It takes 15 minutes everyday to run through this flexibility routine ⬇️

1. 5 Point Hip Flow: start in a half kneeling position reach up and stretch the down knee’s hip flexor for 30 seconds, switch to straight leg hamstring for 30 seconds, switch to half kneeling position and put both hands on the ground - think about laying your chest on the ground here - 30 seconds, open chest and reach to the ceiling with right hand for 10 seconds, switch to the left hand for 10 seconds and repeat the whole cycle on the opposite leg. 
2. Pigeon Stretch: 30 seconds each side 
3. 90|90 Hip Extension with internal hip rotation and knee extension 10 reps each side 
4. Downward Dog Calf Stretch 30 seconds each calf 
5. Hip Floss: lay on your back and grab the back of one leg and extend your knee into a straight leg position for 10 reps then flex and extend your ankle for 10 reps while you keep your leg straight, repeat on both legs
6. Thoracic Opener 10 reps each side
7. Foam Roll & Trigger Point for 5 minutes - wherever you feel necessary.

Push|Pull sleds & flip tires, you’ll feel better. 

These options will allow you to train more without overtraining. You are able to use these for various purposes such as a warmup, anaerobic capacity, aerobic capacity, posterior chain development, & recovery is the main reason why these are top on my list. 

Warm up for your squat day with a 100m tire flip or 200m push or pull for your upper/lower days. 

Anaerobic capacity - do sled sprints. 

Aerobic capacity - pull or push or flip for 20-30 minutes at a maintainable rate.

Posterior chain development - heavy sled pull or push (or if you have a heavy tire - heavy flips) for 40-60 yards of squat or deadlift days. 

Recovery - pull or push nonstop for 30-40 minutes with lighter weight that the aerobic capacity (alternate with forward, backward, lateral pulling/pushing).

🇺🇸Welcoming myself to the  2023 USA National Team. This one was personal. This journey was a perfect example of high and lows, comebacks and bounce backs. I thought at one point in my life I left competitive sports in high school…well here we are and the journey has been sweet and excruciating both mentally and physically. In 2020 I made the preliminary roster for Team USA. But I convinced myself I had no business being there. I felt like I didn’t belong among these athletes. I just wasn’t good enough in my mind. My play respectfully reflected my heart and mind. My ego took a huge hit after that showing and I really didn’t feel like playing for awhile after and I fully invested in the idea of not being good enough. But then I started to realize my @official_ladyvenom team still believed in me. So I bounced back and dove all in…again. Flash forward about 6 months and we showed up to World’s and I felt ready. Friday night January 21st, 2022 I made a big play - pick 6 & I knew I was in that flow state. The very next possession I broke my leg. Idk what it was about being so high to being so low literally trying to crawl off the field unnoticed and out of the way. My mind again switched to ‘am I done done?’ & well let’s just skip the rest of the story because…it’s still not done.

The overall aim for my training is to be as well rounded as possible this stems from simply intentional breathing to being as strong and athletic as possible + all the other good stuff in between. 

Let’s cover training chest today. 

•I always start chest day with some mobility work on my shoulders - facepulls and internal & external rotation. 

•Followed by the big power move for me - bench press. Lately I have been doing the following schemes: week 1 - 7|5|3 wave, week 2 - 5|3|1 wave, week 3 - 3|2|1 wave, week 4 - sets of 5, week 5 - sets of 3, week 6 - sets of 1, & repeat starting back at week one and all your weights should move up (be accountable & track everything).

•Then I focus on building mass for the rest of the workout and incline pressing has been at the top of the list for me. Improving upper pec strength and size adds strength to your flat press, improves stability of the shoulder joints, & creates a better aesthetic appearance. 

•At the end I will doing a fly movement and a couple triceps exercises (maybe on the tris 🙃). & don’t forget your core work - my go to’s are plank variations & Ab wheel. 

If you want to streamline your training and progress send me a dm!

Pull ups have always been a staple in my training, I remember being in middle school convincing my mom to get me one of those captains chair just so I could work on my pull ups. She got it and it sat in my room as a clothes hanger more than anything, flash forward to high school and I could get one good pull up in but it was an all out effort, face red and head veins popping. So I downloaded an app on my phone that told me how many pull ups I had to do a day to be able to do a consecutive set of 10 pull ups. It went something like 1,1,1,3,1,2,2,1,3,etc.. I never even made it to 10 consecutive pull ups until I was in college just because I didn’t understand the importance of consistency I was expecting day 3 to serve up a set of 10 and I got disheartened to only do 1.5 and still with a wildly inappropriate struggle according to my standards at the time. Now, flash forward to my life now and there are still times where I struggle to hit a consecutive set of 10+ if I am not doing them consistently. I say it all the time - we are only good at the things we do most often. So, if you want to be good at pull ups you have to do them - body weight, assisted, negatives, holds, weighted, etc… all the things that suck in the beginning, those are the requirements. I don’t make the rules I just follow them.

This was my “failed” attempt at 75 hard. 
Nothing about life is ever going to be linear and that’s ok. Progress can still be made. Regardless of the obstacles that inevitably popped up in my life, I bounced back into my routine. I stopped looking at everything as a “had to” task and reminded myself daily that my new perspective was the ideology of enjoyment & betterment. My focus shifted and my new intention was to be more present, simpler, and slower. Yes, I 100% believe that my quality of life is dependent on my bodies physical capabilities! But, the concept doesn’t end within the physical - it’s necessary but not all that’s necessary. My mental state was tied into perception but the wrong side of perception. I was constantly at odds with whose opinion and perception of me matter was it your’s or was it mine? We all know the right answer but we all don’t hold ourselves accountable to the follow through. The space we hold for internal dialogue that’s not unnecessarily harsh. Yes, I believe in setting quality standards for myself and to some they maybe strict and high standards, but to me they are what I hold myself to because I know I’m capable. 

Anyways, here’s a little run through of what was included in my version of 75 hard:

•progress picture and weigh in every morning
•drink 1 gallon of water everyday
•follow macros everyday
•15,000 steps everyday
•workout (anywhere & style) everyday
•workout outdoor everyday 
•read 10 pages everyday
•read for 10 minutes everyday

The meat & potatoes of any strength training day (using back day as an example) - I always start with my little warm up here it was a single arm seated cable row. My goal is getting blood flow to the muscles I’m focusing on and creating the initial mind muscle connection I will rely on the rest of the session, so it is extremely common for my to use really slow tempos and pauses during my warm up. 

Next, I go to my big compound lift and on this day I use pull ups. Lately, because I want to focus on strength and size I will do some weighted sets, body weight sets, and assisted sets. (However I do switch every other back day - one day in the split my focus is pull ups and the other back down in the split I focus on heavy barbell rows). Typically I will do anything from 3-6 sets here. 

Moving on with the rest of the workout. I do what feels right. Since there are two back days every six days I like to use one day for horizontal pulling and one day for vertical pulling. Aside from the movements, I’m much more concerned with the quality of the movement now. So time under tension, tempo, drop sets, pauses, partials, etc… all these manipulations of exercise reps I am using often. (Since I already focused on strength development with my big compound lift, now I focus on muscular size development for the rest of the workout.) 

My workouts typically take 45-90 minutes to complete. My rest is minimal (basically the time it takes for nik to complete her set).

Today let’s focus on the lat pulldown. 

When I’m performing this exercise I don’t implement it to build strength or power. Can you? I’m sure. Do I use progressive overload principle with this exercise? Absolutely. 

My main focus with this movement is to stimulate muscular size. 

How? 

Number 1: my tempo stays consistent, not super slow (the slower the better in my opinion - how slow is dependent of your strength and discipline). The weight should be something you can manage and keep control of at least for the majority of your reps. If the last couple reps start to require a little extra - that’s ok as long as you aren’t going wild. 

Number 2: mind muscle connection, I’m focused on making sure I’m feeling the contraction in the right muscles. This movement is primarily to focus on your lats, so the first thing you should feel is your lats burning, later in your sets and reps it would be normal to feel it in your biceps and forearms. If I’m having a hard time getting the right mind muscle connection I will either  drop the weight (and progressively add the weight back on), switch to a one arm variation to use my other hand to feel|tap the muscle to get better connected, or switch movements all together (I’m not married to any specific movement). 

Number 3: proper movement pattern|mechanics, basically making sure my body is moving throughout the exercise correctly. For this exercise my main focus is scapular/shoulder depression - pushing my shoulders down into my back pocket to initiate the movement. I use this motion for as long as possible and then follow through with elbow flexion (bending your elbows) to finish the last portion of the exercise. Once I pull down as far as possible, making sure all the tension stays on my lats, I’m moving through the eccentric portion of the exercise (lengthening of my lats and arms) with total control through the largest range of motion I can while still maintaining lat tension. & repeat.

I look at life differently than I did a couple months ago, & even more differently than a few years ago. I spend more time outside than I ever have, I’m barefoot more often than not, & I eat a lot of food that come from the ground or homemade.

Let’s talk training methods & intensifiers 👇🏽

3 main ways to intensify your workouts include extenders, density, & style. They each serve a different purpose and I was/am one of those people who would just throw things in just for the heck of it to make it hard for no definite purpose other than to just do hard things. Now, I still do that to this day and I don’t really think there’s anything wrong with it as long as you aren’t putting yourself in a position to unnecessarily injury yourself or cause yourself to hate training. 

So let’s dig into what the purpose of each is: 

Set extenders are techniques like drop set variations & rest pause sets. These are used to “extend” your set without doing reps that are wasteful (do not promote hypertrophy). Control & connection will lead to more muscle growth than sloppy volume. I tend to add these as the last 1-2 sets of big movements like squats, rows, and presses.

Density includes superset variations, giant sets, and circuits. These are used to cut down the time it takes to perform more volume. (Like I’m doing in the reel) Typically I don’t use these unless I want to get in and out of the gym. So if you are on a time restriction use antagonist supersets like chest and back or quads and hamstrings. Even giant sets that include everything like squats, overhead press, RDLs, and pull ups. None of the exercises should impact the strength of each other because they are all targeting different aspects of the body. Rest time is shortened because while one muscle is working the other is resting. 

Style includes techniques like pause reps, partials, and tempos. I will use these for strength development and hypertrophy. Most of my tempo work is during the eccentric loading phase - slow everything down. A good use for a tempo set is when you hit a strength plateau. This would be when you are stuck on an exercise and you can’t do anymore reps and you cant quite do anymore weight either - so to break through that plateau use a slow eccentric tempo (~3-8 seconds) and a pause at peak contraction (~1-4 seconds) for about 6-20 reps and you’ll break through that plateau.

I’ve spent a lot of time on my delt development and one thing I have found to be pretty tried and true for myself is how much volume your shoulders can take and how much they like. I use both volume and mass while training shoulders & sometimes I do both! Follow this little set extender variation I used for shoulder press this week to see what I mean👇🏽

One my last heavy working set I used a rest pause method then turned it into a drop set. 

To give full context for this exercise I performed 6 total sets my first 4 sets are sets I use to warm up with and work up to two heavy all out working sets. 

Set 1: 20 reps 
Set 2: 20 reps (add weight)
Set 3: 15 reps (add weight)
Set 4: 15 reps (add weight) 
Set 5: 10 reps (add weight - heavy working set)
Set 6: added more weight and performed a rest pause set + drop set 

Let’s zone in specifically on set 6. 

First, I added weight because I know my form would be able to handle the jump up in weight. & this is my only movement I focus on strength development for shoulders so I’m inclined to add weight when possible. 

Next, let’s focus on how to perform this set extender variation. Using my heavier working set weight I performed as many reps as possible - I didn’t let my form deviate too much. Once I failed, I rested for 15 seconds, keeping the same weight I again performed as many reps as possible. Once I failed for the second time I dropped some weight off of each side (25lbs each side) and again performed as many reps as possible to failure. I only rested long enough to take the weigh off of each side before I started my final cluster of reps. 

Give it a shot and let me know how your shoulders took it.

I want to explain a little behind my workout design. I have some staples and then I have some free flow to each workout. Staples include exercises like squats, bench, deadlift, shoulder press, and pull ups. Then there’s staples like never perform bent over barbell rows the back day before deadlifts. Which leads me to yesterdays workout flow for back day. 

This reel was the last exercise superset I performed. 

This full workout 👇🏽

Wide Grip Pulldown 
2x15
2x10
1x Rest Pause Set 
1x Rest Pause Triple Drop Set 

Seated Row 
2x15
2x10 

Superset:
A) Half Kneeling Cable High Row 
5x10 each arm
B) Neutral Grip Explosive Pull Ups 
5x3 reset every rep

Superset:
A) Single Arm Seated Cable Row
5x10 each arm 
B) Assisted Pull Ups 
5x10 

The thoughts behind the last two supersets - I love to pair vertical pulling with horizontal pulling. I don’t expect to max out when I’m doing these together. I just look to have a solid mind muscle connection for as long as possible. Fatigue will hinder you, and that’s ok. I’m looking to use those last couple hard reps at the end of each set to grow from. 

In the first superset I do a horizontal pulling exercise from a high position paired with a vertical pulling (neutral grip pull ups). Then I thought a great compliment to these would be a horizontal pulling exercise from a low position (single arm seated cable row) paired with another vertical pulling exercise (assisted pull ups). Side Note: this is the back day before a deadlift day. 

The flow of my exercise selection has variance each week but I always stay true to my staples. Don’t stress yourself out too much on exercise selection for every aspect of the workout. Pick your staples and focus on your progressive overload with them but still allow yourself to have fun with the rest of the workout and get creative. Use angles, tempos, and variations to your advantage.

I always following a similar outline for my strength training sessions. 👇🏽

First 5 minutes - warm up, anything that needs attention to prep for the heavy compound gets get. 

Next - heavy compound, each week follows the same scheme (for the past 12 weeks) 7-5-3 wave, 5-3-1 wave, 3-2-1 wave, sets of 5, sets of 3, & sets of 1. Each week I move from one scheme to the next in that order. 

Middle - I use the section of time to focus on building as much muscle as possible. Like for this reel - after I did flat bench and some incline DB press I performed one massive circuit with flys(15 reps), push ups(10 tempo reps), & dips(5 reps). 4 sets & I was 🍳. 

End of workout - if there’s anything I feel like needs a little extra work (core and side delts typically) I will do a little extra. Plus 10 minutes in the sauna!

👀Just a little perspective on how I perform leg curls 

•I keep the eccentric tempo slow and controlled
•I keep my glutes contracted the entire rep
•I keep my hips pressed into the pad the entire rep 
•I avoid allowing my lower back and calves from overcompensating by engaging my glutes and abs while letting my ankles relax

Typical rep & set scheme for me lately👇🏽
1-2 sets of 20 (these sets are to push blood into the muscle and build a mind muscle connection) 
1-2 sets of 15 (increase weight from the sets of 20 and focus on maintaining good form and controlled tempo)
1-2 sets of 10 (increase weight from sets of 10 and still focus on form and tempo but these are my heavy sets, so I’m trying to move weight) 
1 sets of a rest pause set with heavier weight (this is something I do to get familiar with heavier loads) I perform as many reps as possible to failure, rest for 10-15 seconds and go again for as many reps as possible 
*if I’m feeling good I will add a drop set in. 
1 drop set using 3-4 different weights going to failure with each weight without resting between each weight change.
